{"cursor":"19810","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox\nperson |name = Wiley Post |image = Wiley Post cph.3b33667.jpg |image_size =\n|caption = |birth_date = Wiley Hardeman Post |birth_place = Van Zandt\nCounty, Texas, U.S.A. |death_date = |death_place = Point Barrow, Alaska, U.S.A.\n|occupation = Aviator |spouse = Mae Laine (m. June 27, 1927) |parents = William\nFrancis Post and Mae Quinlan Post }} aircraft of Wiley Post, when it was on\ndisplay at the Steven F. Udvar-Hazy Center]]\n\n'Wiley Hardeman Post' (November 22, 1898 – August 15, 1935) was a famed\nAmerican aviator, the first pilot to fly solo around the world. Also known for\nhis work in high altitude flying, Post helped develop one of the first pressure\nsuits and discovered the jet stream. On August 15, 1935, Post and American\nhumorist Will Rogers were killed when Post's aircraft crashed on takeoff from a\nlagoon near Point Barrow in the Territory of Alaska.\n\nPosts Lockheed Vega aircraft, the Winnie Mae, was on display at the National Air\nand Space Museum's Steven F. Udvar-Hazy Center from 2003 to 2011. It will be\nfeatured in the new \"Time and Navigation\" gallery at the National Air and Space\nMuseum in early 2013.\n","linknr":314,"url":"Wiley_Post","recorded":1362584637,"links":33,"instances":["oil_industrialist","philately","usa","blatchford_field_airport"],"pdf":["http://www.sil.si.edu/smithsoniancontributions/AnnalsofFlight/pdf_lo/SAOF-0008.pdf"],"categories":["American aviators","Aviation pioneers","Aviators from Texas","Accidental deaths in Alaska","Aviators killed in aviation accidents or incidents in the United States","Harmon Trophy winners","National Aviation Hall of Fame inductees","Oklahoma Hall of Fame inductees","Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)","People from Van Zandt County, Texas","People from Oklahoma","1898 births","1935 deaths"],"headings":["Early life","Early flying career","Around the world","Pressure suit","Final flight and